NE_counties_sf <- st_read('./Data/Spatial/cb_2018_us_county_20m.shp') %>%

  1. What is the EPSG code of the Counties dataset? Is this a geographic or a projected coordinate reference system? (Or, does this CRS use angular or planar coordinate units?) To what datum is this CRS associated? (Tip: look at the EPSG code on https://spatialreference.org)

ANSWER: The EPSG code for the Counties dataset is 4269, representing a projected coordinate reference system that uses planar coordinate units (meters) and belongs to the North American Datum of 1983 (NAD83).

Read in the gage height data and join the site location data to it.

Lastly, we want to attach some gage height data to our site locations. Ive constructed a csv file listing many of the Nebraska gage sites, by station name and site number along with stream gage heights (in meters) recorded during the recent flood event. This file is titled NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv and is found in the Data/Raw folder.

  1. Read in and wrangle the NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv dataset:
  • Be sure the site_no column is read in as a factor
  • Group by site_no and station_nm, computing the mean gage_ht across groups values
  1. Show the column names .
  2. Join our site information (already imported above) to these gage height data.
  • The site_no and station_nm can both/either serve as joining attributes.
  • Construct this join so that the result only includes spatial features where both tables have data.
  1. Show the column names in this resulting spatial features object
  2. Show the dimensions of the resulting joined dataframe
#14. Read the site flow data into a data frame
NWIS_NE_SiteFlow <- read.csv('./Data/Raw/NWIS_SiteFlowData_NE_RAW.csv', 
  colClasses = c('site_no' = 'factor')) %>%
  group_by(site_no, station_nm) %>%
  summarize(Mean_gage_ht = mean(gage_ht, na.rm = T)) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'site_no'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
#15. Show the column names
colnames(NWIS_NE_SiteFlow)
## [1] "site_no"      "station_nm"   "Mean_gage_ht"
#16. Join the flow data to our NWIS gage location spatial dataframe
NWIS_NE_Site_Join <- merge(x = NWIS_NE_gages_sf,
                           y = NWIS_NE_SiteFlow,
                           by.x = "site_no",
                           by.y = "site_no")

#17. Show the column names of the joined dataset
colnames(NWIS_NE_Site_Join)
## [1] "site_no"            "station_nm.x"       "site_tp_cd"        
## [4] "coord_acy_cd"       "dec_coord_datum_cd" "station_nm.y"      
## [7] "Mean_gage_ht"       "geometry"
#18. Show the dimensions of this joined dataset
dim(NWIS_NE_Site_Join)
## [1] 118   8

Map the pattern of gage height data

Now we can examine where the flooding appears most acute by visualizing gage heights spatially. 19. Plot the gage sites on top of counties (using mapview, ggplot, or leaflet) * Show the magnitude of gage height by color, shape, or other visualization technique.

#Map the points, colored by gage height
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data = NE_counties_sf, fill = "white") + 
  geom_sf(data = NWIS_NE_Site_Join, aes(color = Mean_gage_ht)) +
  guides(colour = guide_legend(title="Mean Gage Height in Feet")) +
  labs(title = "Mean Gage Height by County in Nebraska") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "top")

SPATIAL ANALYSIS

Up next we will do some spatial analysis with our data. To prepare for this, we should transform our data into a projected coordinate system. Well choose UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).

Transform the counties and gage site datasets to UTM Zone 14N

  1. Transform the counties and gage sf datasets to UTM Zone 14N (EPGS = 32614).
  2. Using mapview or ggplot, plot the data so that each can be seen as different colors
#20 Transform the counties and gage location datasets to UTM Zone 14
NWIS_NE_gages_UTM <- st_transform(NWIS_NE_gages_sf, crs = 32614) 
NWIS_NE_counties_UTM <- st_transform(NE_counties_sf, crs = 32614)

#21 Plot the data
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = NWIS_NE_counties_UTM, fill = "yellow") +
  geom_sf(data = NWIS_NE_gages_UTM, color = "blue") +
  labs(title = "Water Gage Locations in Nebraska by County") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Select the gages falling within a given county

Now lets zoom into a particular county and examine the gages located there. 22. Select Douglas county from your projected county sf dataframe 23. Select the gage sites falling within that county * Use either matrix subsetting or tidy filtering 24. #22 Select the county
NWIS_Douglas <- NWIS_NE_counties_UTM %>%
